node.text:
In this episode, we’re headed to Queenstown, New Zealand with Megan Duncan of @touchofspice_nz, Luxury Stays and Experiences. “Queenstown is known as an outdoor playground. We’ve got everything from skiing in the winter to mountain biking in the summer—there are so many walking tracks right from your front door.” Tag along as she walks through downtown Queenstown, around the Remarkables Market, and shows off the spectacular views of the city and Lake Wakatipu from the base of Ben Lomond.

Where should we go next?

More than thirty years after the fall of the Berlin Wall, the German capital's intoxicating mix of grit, glamour, and anything-goes expression born from historical repression has made it one of the most dynamic cities on earth. Bring an open mind, pack your stamina, and get ready to dive into all the city has to offer—link in bio for our list of the best things to do in Berlin for all your future trip needs.

#MyFavoriteAirbnb: A cowboy-themed tiny house in Iowa. “How, exactly, on a road trip from Los Angeles to New York, did I end up here, showering behind a farm house in Clayton County, Iowa? I wish I could say it was serendipity. When plotting out the route of a 10-day cross-country road trip with my partner this summer, I had taken to using @Airbnb's map feature to search for standout stays worth planning our overnight stops around. When dragging my cursor between Omaha and Milwaukee, I found something called “The Tack Shed:” An actual tack room—filled with saddles, bridles, and even a pair of chaps—plopped between the horse pastures. The 12-by-14-foot structure, “constructed almost entirely from reclaimed or home-sawn materials,” according to the listing, had also been outfitted with a loft bed, a partial kitchen, a few couches, and the aforementioned outdoor shower. We booked immediately. It turned out to be the most memorable stay of our trip.”

Keep reading, and book a stay at The Tack Shed for yourself, at the link in bio. 

📷: @resilentos, video by @spurrelly

The oldest city in Georgia, Savannah is home to one of the largest Historic Landmark Districts in the United States. The district serves as the hub of downtown, with 22 verdant city squares, cobblestone streets, and myriad 18th- and 19th-century monuments and buildings. But what locals (and clever travelers) know, is that the historic district is only the beginning. At the link in bio, find our list of the best things to do in Savannah, from museums to food trucks. 

📷: @photobyshannon

The main draw of Alberobello, a small town near Bari in Puglia, is its characteristic trulli: cone-shaped, white-tipped houses that look as if they’ve been perpetually dusted by snow. Thanks to this distinctive feature, the town was deemed so unique that it was made a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1996. 

Few parts of the world can claim such a range of natural beauty as Italy—at the link in bio see our list of the most beautiful spots. 

📷: @bmseventh

For sandy beaches and legendary surf conditions, to historic lighthouses, shipwreck diving sites, and wild horses, the Outer Banks is a unique East Coast beach vacation. No single island or town bears the official name Outer Banks—rather, the term refers to the string of barrier islands cupping North Carolina’s entire coast, a divide between the inland and the Atlantic.
Born of 19th-century fishing villages and game hunting retreats, this destination now provides a year-round haven for surfers, artists, environmental researchers, families, and retirees. At the link in bio, find our guide for what to do in Outer Banks, and everything else you need to know to plan a visit. 

📷: @dccitygirl

We interviewed her as part of #TheWorldMadeLocal, a global collaboration between the seven international editions of Condé Nast Traveler in which 100 people in 100 countries tell us why their home turf should be your next destination.

At the link in bio, read Cecilia’s guide on how to tackle the Norwegian island all year long.

Venice has often been likened to an open-air museum—and starting next year, it might feel like one, too. Last week, the local administration of La Serenissima announced that, from the second half of 2022, it will limit the number of visitors to its narrow calli and iconic piazzas by putting a cap on day trippers. Electronic turnstiles at entry points and a dedicated booking app are also being introduced. The measure is the latest effort to preserve Venice’s fragile ecosystem, and curb the overtourism it suffered from in pre-pandemic years. It follows the ban on large cruise ships that came into effect on August 1, and the recent decision by the Italian government to make the lagoon a national monument, so as to place it under enhanced state protection.

Keep reading about what this means for travelers at the link in bio.

📷: @thomas_k

node.text: Rome may be an ancient city, but its hotel scene is as up-to-date as befits the capital of Italy. A high-minded hostel that’s halfway to being a hotel, the opportunity to bed down in a former monastery, a couple of private penthouse residences with discreet, as-you-please service, and plenty of blow-out luxury abodes: the city's options span an eclectic mix of design, glamour, and all-out Italian inspiration. To help you get started, we've picked some of the best hotels in Rome for your next trip. Link in bio.

node.text:
It may be one of the smaller continents, but what Europe lacks in size, it makes up for in variety: The most beautiful places in Europe range from luxurious beaches, fields of bluebells, and limestone cliffs, to some of the best mountain views on the planet. The options are seemingly endless—which is what makes planning a trip a challenge. To help you start narrowing things down, we've rounded up just 27 of the most beautiful places in Europe. We know that an international jaunt might be off the table at the moment, but hey—that'll just give you more time to plot out your next trip. Link in bio. 

📷: @chrisroams
